M|Data|**An|Think of Claude as a robot exploring a path:
M|Data|* **|There's only one safe way forward. Provide specific guardrails and exact instructions (lo freedom). Example: db migrations that must run in exact sequence.
M|Data|* **|Many paths lead to sc. Give general direction and trust Claude to find the best rt (hi freedom). Example: code reviews where context determines the best approach.
M|Test|tx|Skills act as additions to md, so effectiveness depends on the underlying md. tst your Skill w/ all the md you plan to use it w/.
M|Test|**Te|
M|Test|* **|Does the Skill provide enough guidance?
M|Test|* **|Is the Skill clear and efficient?
M|Test|* **|Does the Skill avoid over-explaining?
M|Test|tx|What works perfectly for Opus might need more detail for Haiku. If you plan to use your Skill across multiple md, aim for instructions that work well w/ all of them.
M|Skil|tx|<Note>
M|Skil|**YA|The SKILL.md frontmatter requires two fields:
M|Skil|it|`name` - Human-readable name of the Skill (64 characters maximum)
M|Skil|it|`description` - One-line description of what the Skill does and when to use it (1024 characters maximum)
M|Skil|tx|For complete Skill structure details, see the [Skills overview](/en/doc/ag-and-tools/ag-skills/overview#skill-structure).
M|Skil|tx|</Note>
M|Nami|tx|Use consistent naming patterns to make Skills easier to reference and discuss. We recommend using **gerund form** (verb + -ing) for Skill names, as this clearly describes the activity or capability the Skill provides.
M|Nami|**Go|
M|Nami|it|"Processing PDFs"
M|Nami|it|"Analyzing spreadsheets"
M|Nami|it|"Managing databases"
M|Nami|it|"Testing code"
M|Nami|it|"Writing doc"
M|Nami|**Ac|
M|Nami|* No|"PDF Processing", "Spreadsheet al"
M|Nami|* Ac|"Process PDFs", "al Spreadsheets"
M|Nami|**Av|
M|Nami|* Va|"Helper", "Utils", "Tools"
M|Nami|* Ov|"Documents", "Data", "Files"
M|Nami|it|Inconsistent patterns within your skill collection
M|Nami|Cons|
M|Nami|it|Reference Skills in doc and conversations
M|Nami|it|Understand what a Skill does at a glance
M|Nami|it|Organize and search through multiple Skills
M|Nami|it|Maintain a professional, cohesive skill library
M|Writ|tx|The `description` field enables Skill discovery and shd include both what the Skill does and when to use it.
M|Writ|tx|<wn>
M|Writ|tx|**Always write in third person**. The description is injected into the sy pm, and inconsistent point-of-view can cause discovery problems.
M|Writ|* **|** "Processes Excel files and generates reports"
M|Writ|* **|** "I can help you process Excel files"
M|Writ|* **|** "You can use this to process Excel files"
M|Writ|tx|</wn>
M|Writ|tx|**Be specific and include key terms**. Include both what the Skill does and specific triggers/contexts for when to use it.
M|Writ|Each|Claude uses it to choose the right Skill from potentially 100+ available Skills. Your description must provide enough detail for Claude to know when to select this Skill, while the rest of SKILL.md provides the implementation details.
M|Writ|Effe|
M|Writ|**PD|**
M|Writ|tx|```yaml  theme={null}
M|Writ|desc|Extract text and tables from PDF files, fill forms, merge documents. Use when working w/ PDF files or when the us mentions PDFs, forms, or document extraction.
M|Writ|tx|```
M|Writ|**Ex|**
M|Writ|tx|```yaml  theme={null}
M|Writ|desc|al Excel spreadsheets, cr pivot tables, gn charts. Use when analyzing Excel files, spreadsheets, tabular data, or .xlsx files.
M|Writ|tx|```
M|Writ|**Gi|**
M|Writ|tx|```yaml  theme={null}
M|Writ|desc|gn descriptive commit messages by analyzing git diffs. Use when the us asks for help writing commit messages or reviewing staged changes.
M|Writ|tx|```
M|Writ|Avoi|
