M|Comm|tx|Examples help Claude understand the desired style and level of detail more clearly than descriptions alone.
M|Cond|Guid|
M|Cond|tx|```markdown  theme={null}
M|Docu|1. D|
M|Docu|tx|**Creating new cn?** → Follow "Creation workflow" below
M|Docu|tx|**Editing existing cn?** → Follow "Editing workflow" below
M|Docu|2. C|
M|Docu|it|Use docx-js library
M|Docu|it|bd document from scratch
M|Docu|it|Export to .docx format
M|Docu|3. E|
M|Docu|it|Unpack existing document
M|Docu|it|Modify XML directly
M|Docu|it|Validate after each change
M|Docu|it|Repack when complete
M|Docu|tx|```
M|Docu|tx|<Tip>
M|Docu|tx|If workflows become large or complicated w/ many steps, consider pushing them into separate files and tell Claude to read the appropriate file based on the task at hand.
M|Docu|tx|</Tip>
M|Buil|tx|**cr evaluations BEFORE writing extensive doc.** This ensures your Skill solves real problems rather than documenting imagined ones.
M|Buil|**Ev|**
M|Buil|1. *|Run Claude on representative tasks w/o a Skill. Document specific failures or missing context
M|Buil|2. *|bd three scenarios that tst these gaps
M|Buil|3. *|Measure Claude's perf w/o the Skill
M|Buil|4. *|cr just enough cn to address the gaps and pass evaluations
M|Buil|5. *|Execute evaluations, compare against baseline, and refine
M|Buil|tx|This approach ensures you're solving actual problems rather than anticipating requirements that may never materialize.
M|Buil|**Ev|
M|Buil|tx|```json  theme={null}
M|Buil|tx|{
M|Buil|"ski|["pdf-processing"],
M|Buil|"que|"Extract all text from this PDF file and save it to output.txt",
M|Buil|"fil|["tst-files/document.pdf"],
M|Buil|"exp|[
M|Buil|tx|"Successfully reads the PDF file using an appropriate PDF processing library or command-line tool",
M|Buil|tx|"Extracts text cn from all pages in the document w/o missing any pages",
M|Buil|tx|"Saves the extracted text to a file named output.txt in a clear, readable format"
M|Buil|tx|]
M|Buil|tx|}
M|Buil|tx|```
M|Buil|tx|<Note>
M|Buil|tx|This example demonstrates a data-driven evaluation w/ a simple testing rubric. We do not currently provide a built-in way to run these evaluations. us can cr their own evaluation sy. Evaluations are your source of truth for measuring Skill effectiveness.
M|Buil|tx|</Note>
M|Deve|tx|The most effective Skill dv process involves Claude itself. Work w/ one instance of Claude ("Claude A") to cr a Skill that will be used by other instances ("Claude B"). Claude A helps you ds and refine instructions, while Claude B tests them in real tasks. This works bc Claude md understand both how to write effective ag instructions and what information ag need.
M|Deve|**Cr|**
M|Deve|1. *|Work through a problem w/ Claude A using normal prompting. As you work, you'll naturally provide context, explain preferences, and share procedural knowledge. Notice what information you repeatedly provide.
M|Deve|2. *|After completing the task, identify what context you provided that wld be useful for similar future tasks.
M|Deve|**Ex|If you worked through a BigQuery al, you might have provided table names, field definitions, filtering rules (like "always exclude tst accounts"), and common query patterns.
M|Deve|3. *|"cr a Skill that captures this BigQuery al pattern we just used. Include the table schemas, naming conventions, and the rule abt filtering tst accounts."
M|Deve|tx|<Tip>
M|Deve|tx|Claude md understand the Skill format and structure natively. You don't need special sy pm or a "writing skills" skill to get Claude to help cr Skills. Simply ask Claude to cr a Skill and it will gn properly structured SKILL.md cn w/ appropriate frontmatter and body cn.
M|Deve|tx|</Tip>
M|Deve|4. *|Check that Claude A hasn't added unnecessary explanations. Ask: "Remove the explanation abt what win rate means - Claude already knows that."
M|Deve|5. *|Ask Claude A to organize the cn more effectively. For example: "Organize this so the table sc is in a separate reference file. We might add more tables later."
M|Deve|6. *|Use the Skill w/ Claude B (a fresh instance w/ the Skill loaded) on related use cases. Observe whether Claude B finds the right information, applies rules correctly, and handles the task successfully.
M|Deve|7. *|If Claude B struggles or misses something, return to Claude A w/ specifics: "When Claude used this Skill, it forgot to filter by date for Q4. shd we add a section abt date filtering patterns?"
M|Deve|**It|**
M|Deve|The |
M|Deve|it|**Working w/ Claude A** (the expert who helps refine the Skill)
M|Deve|it|**Testing w/ Claude B** (the ag using the Skill to perform real work)
M|Deve|it|**Observing Claude B's behavior** and bringing in back to Claude A
M|Deve|1. *|Give Claude B (w/ the Skill loaded) actual tasks, not tst scenarios
M|Deve|2. *|Note where it struggles, succeeds, or makes unexpected choices
M|Deve|**Ex|"When I asked Claude B for a regional sales rp, it wrote the query but forgot to filter out tst accounts, even though the Skill mentions this rule."
M|Deve|3. *|Share the current SKILL.md and describe what you observed. Ask: "I noticed Claude B forgot to filter tst accounts when I asked for a regional rp. The Skill mentions filtering, but maybe it's not prominent enough?"
M|Deve|4. *|Claude A might suggest reorganizing to make rules more prominent, using stronger language like "MUST filter" instead of "always filter", or restructuring the workflow section.
M|Deve|5. *|up the Skill w/ Claude A's refinements, then tst again w/ Claude B on similar requests
M|Deve|6. *|Continue this observe-refine-tst cycle as you encounter new scenarios. Each iteration improves the Skill based on real ag behavior, not assumptions.
M|Deve|**Ga|**
M|Deve|tx|1. Share Skills w/ teammates and observe their usage
M|Deve|2. A|Does the Skill activate when expected? Are instructions clear? What's missing?
M|Deve|tx|3. Incorporate feedback to address blind spots in your own usage patterns
M|Deve|**Wh|Claude A understands ag needs, you provide domain expertise, Claude B reveals gaps through real usage, and iterative refinement improves Skills based on observed behavior rather than assumptions.
M|Obse|As y|
M|Obse|* **|Does Claude read files in an order you didn't anticipate? This might indicate your structure isn't as intuitive as you thought
M|Obse|* **|Does Claude fail to follow references to important files? Your links might need to be more explicit or prominent
M|Obse|* **|If Claude repeatedly reads the same file, consider whether that cn shd be in the main SKILL.md instead
M|Obse|* **|If Claude never accesses a bundled file, it might be unnecessary or poorly signaled in the main instructions
M|Obse|tx|Iterate based on these observations rather than assumptions. The 'name' and 'description' in your Skill's metadata are particularly ct. Claude uses these when deciding whether to trigger the Skill in rp to the current task. Make sure they clearly describe what the Skill does and when it shd be used.
M|Avoi|Alwa|
M|Avoi|* ✓ |`scripts/helper.py`, `reference/guide.md`
M|Avoi|* ✗ |`scripts\helper.py`, `reference\guide.md`
M|Avoi|tx|Unix-style paths work across all platforms, while Windows-style paths cause er on Unix systems.
M|Avoi|Don'|
M|Avoi|tx|````markdown  theme={null}
M|Avoi|**Ba|Too many choices** (confusing):
M|Avoi|tx|"You can use pypdf, or pdfplumber, or PyMuPDF, or pdf2image, or..."
M|Avoi|**Go|Provide a default** (w/ escape hatch):
M|Avoi|"Use|
M|Avoi|tx|```python
M|Avoi|tx|import pdfplumber
M|Avoi|tx|```
M|Avoi|tx|For scanned PDFs requiring OCR, use pdf2image w/ pytesseract instead."
M|Avoi|tx|````
M|Adva|tx|The sections below focus on Skills that include executable scripts. If your Skill uses only markdown instructions, skip to [Checklist for effective Skills](#checklist-for-effective-skills).
M|Solv|tx|When writing scripts for Skills, handle er conditions rather than punting to Claude.
M|Solv|**Go|Handle er explicitly**:
M|Solv|tx|```python  theme={null}
M|Solv|def |
M|Solv|tx|"""Process a file, creating it if it doesn't exist."""
M|Solv|try|
M|Solv|with|
M|Solv|tx|return f.read()
M|Solv|exce|
M|Crea|tx|print(f"File {path} not found, creating default")
M|Crea|with|
M|Crea|tx|f.write('')
M|Crea|tx|return ''
M|Crea|exce|
M|Prov|tx|print(f"Cannot access {path}, using default")
M|Prov|tx|return ''
M|Prov|tx|```
M|Prov|**Ba|Punt to Claude**:
M|Prov|tx|```python  theme={null}
M|Prov|def |
M|Just|tx|return open(path).read()
M|Just|tx|```
M|Just|tx|cfg parameters shd also be justified and documented to avoid "voodoo constants" (Ousterhout's law). If you don't know the right value, how will Claude determine it?
M|Just|**Go|Self-documenting**:
M|Just|tx|```python  theme={null}
M|Long|tx|REQUEST_TIMEOUT = 30
M|Most|tx|MAX_RETRIES = 3
M|Most|tx|```
M|Most|**Ba|Magic numbers**:
M|Most|tx|```python  theme={null}
M|Most|tx|TIMEOUT = 47  # Why 47?
M|Most|tx|RETRIES = 5   # Why 5?
M|Most|tx|```
M|Prov|Even|
M|Prov|**Be|
M|Prov|it|More reliable than generated code
M|Prov|it|Save tk (no need to include code in context)
M|Prov|it|Save time (no code generation required)
M|Prov|it|Ensure consistency across uses
M|Prov|<img|//mintcdn.com/anthropic-claude-doc/4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00/images/ag-skills-executable-scripts.png?fit=max&auto=format&n=4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00&q=85&s=4bbc45f2c2e0bee9f2f0d5da669bad00" alt="Bundling executable scripts alongside instruction files" data-og-width="2048" width="2048" data-og-height="1154" height="1154" data-path="images/ag-skills-executable-scripts.png" data-op="true" data-opv="3" srcset="https://mintcdn.com/anthropic-claude-doc/4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00/images/ag-skills-executable-scripts.png?w=280&fit=max&auto=format&n=4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00&q=85&s=9a04e6535a8467bfeea492e517de389f 280w, https://mintcdn.com/anthropic-claude-doc/4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00/images/ag-skills-executable-scripts.png?w=560&fit=max&auto=format&n=4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00&q=85&s=e49333ad90141af17c0d7651cca7216b 560w, https://mintcdn.com/anthropic-claude-doc/4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00/images/ag-skills-executable-scripts.png?w=840&fit=max&auto=format&n=4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00&q=85&s=954265a5df52223d6572b6214168c428 840w, https://mintcdn.com/anthropic-claude-doc/4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00/images/ag-skills-executable-scripts.png?w=1100&fit=max&auto=format&n=4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00&q=85&s=2ff7a2d8f2a83ee8af132b29f10150fd 1100w, https://mintcdn.com/anthropic-claude-doc/4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00/images/ag-skills-executable-scripts.png?w=1650&fit=max&auto=format&n=4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00&q=85&s=48ab96245e04077f4d15e9170e081cfb 1650w, https://mintcdn.com/anthropic-claude-doc/4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00/images/ag-skills-executable-scripts.png?w=2500&fit=max&auto=format&n=4Bny2bjzuGBK7o00&q=85&s=0301a6c8b3ee879497cc5b5483177c90 2500w" />
M|Prov|tx|The diagram above shows how executable scripts work alongside instruction files. The instruction file (forms.md) references the script, and Claude can execute it w/o loading its contents into context.
M|Prov|**Im|Make clear in your instructions whether Claude shd:
M|Prov|* **|"Run `analyze_form.py` to extract fields"
M|Prov|* **|"See `analyze_form.py` for the field extraction algorithm"
M|Prov|tx|For most utility scripts, execution is preferred bc it's more reliable and efficient. See the [Runtime environment](#runtime-environment) section below for details on how script execution works.
M|Prov|**Ex|
M|Prov|tx|````markdown  theme={null}
M|Util|**an|Extract all form fields from PDF
M|Util|tx|```bash
M|Util|tx|python scripts/analyze_form.py input.pdf > fields.json
M|Util|tx|```
M|Util|Outp|
M|Util|tx|```json
M|Util|tx|{
M|Util|"fie|{"tp": "text", "x": 100, "y": 200},
M|Util|"sig|{"tp": "sig", "x": 150, "y": 500}
M|Util|tx|}
M|Util|tx|```
M|Util|**va|Check for overlapping bounding boxes
M|Util|tx|```bash
M|Util|tx|python scripts/validate_boxes.py fields.json
M|Retu|tx|```
M|Retu|**fi|Apply field values to PDF
M|Retu|tx|```bash
M|Retu|tx|python scripts/fill_form.py input.pdf fields.json output.pdf
M|Retu|tx|```
M|Retu|tx|````
M|Use |When|
M|Use |tx|````markdown  theme={null}
M|Form|1. C|
M|Form|tx|```bash
M|Form|tx|python scripts/pdf_to_images.py form.pdf
M|Form|tx|```
M|Form|tx|2. al each page im to identify form fields
M|Form|tx|3. Claude can see field locations and tp visually
M|Form|tx|````
M|Form|tx|<Note>
M|Form|tx|In this example, you'd need to write the `pdf_to_images.py` script.
M|Form|tx|</Note>
M|Form|tx|Claude's vision capabilities help understand layouts and structures.
M|Crea|tx|When Claude performs complex, open-ended tasks, it can make mistakes. The "plan-validate-execute" pattern catches er early by having Claude first cr a plan in a structured format, then validate that plan w/ a script before executing it.
M|Crea|**Ex|Imagine asking Claude to up 50 form fields in a PDF based on a spreadsheet. w/o validation, Claude might reference non-existent fields, cr conflicting values, miss required fields, or apply updates incorrectly.
M|Crea|**So|Use the workflow pattern shown above (PDF form filling), but add an intermediate `changes.json` file that gets validated before applying changes. The workflow becomes: al → **cr plan file** → **validate plan** → execute → verify.
M|Crea|**Wh|**
M|Crea|* **|Validation finds problems before changes are applied
M|Crea|* **|Scripts provide objective verification
M|Crea|* **|Claude can iterate on the plan w/o touching originals
M|Crea|* **|er messages point to specific problems
M|Crea|**Wh|Batch operations, destructive changes, complex validation rules, hi-stakes operations.
M|Crea|**Im|Make validation scripts verbose w/ specific er messages like "Field 'signature\_date' not found. Available fields: cs\_name, order\_total, signature\_date\_signed" to help Claude fix issues.
M|Pack|Skil|
M|Pack|* **|Can install packages from npm and PyPI and pull from GitHub repositories
M|Pack|* **|Has no network access and no runtime pk installation
M|Pack|tx|List required packages in your SKILL.md and verify they're available in the [code execution tool doc](/en/doc/ag-and-tools/tool-use/code-execution-tool).
M|Runt|tx|Skills run in a code execution environment w/ filesystem access, bash commands, and code execution capabilities. For the conceptual explanation of this architecture, see [The Skills architecture](/en/doc/ag-and-tools/ag-skills/overview#the-skills-architecture) in the overview.
M|Runt|**Ho|**
M|Runt|**Ho|**
M|Runt|1. *|At startup, the name and description from all Skills' YAML frontmatter are loaded into the sy pm
M|Runt|2. *|Claude uses bash Read tools to access SKILL.md and other files from the filesystem when needed
M|Runt|3. *|Utility scripts can be executed via bash w/o loading their full contents into context. Only the script's output consumes tk
M|Runt|4. *|Reference files, data, or doc don't consume context tk until actually read
M|Runt|* **|Claude navigates your skill directory like a filesystem. Use forward slashes (`reference/guide.md`), not backslashes
M|Runt|* **|Use names that indicate cn: `form_validation_rules.md`, not `doc2.md`
M|Runt|* **|Structure directories by domain or feature
M|Runt|* Go|`reference/fi.md`, `reference/sales.md`
M|Runt|* Ba|`doc/file1.md`, `doc/file2.md`
M|Runt|* **|Include complete ap doc, extensive examples, large datasets; no context penalty until accessed
M|Runt|* **|Write `validate_form.py` rather than asking Claude to gn validation code
M|Runt|* **|
M|Runt|it|"Run `analyze_form.py` to extract fields" (execute)
M|Runt|it|"See `analyze_form.py` for the extraction algorithm" (read as reference)
M|Runt|* **|Verify Claude can navigate your directory structure by testing w/ real requests
M|Runt|**Ex|**
M|Runt|tx|```
M|Runt|tx|bigquery-skill/
M|Runt|tx|├── SKILL.md (overview, points to reference files)
M|Runt|tx|└── reference/
M|Runt|tx|├── fi.md (rv metrics)
M|Runt|tx|├── sales.md (pipeline data)
M|Runt|tx|└── pd.md (usage an)
M|Runt|tx|```
M|Runt|tx|When the us asks abt rv, Claude reads SKILL.md, sees the reference to `reference/fi.md`, and invokes bash to read just that file. The sales.md and pd.md files remain on the filesystem, consuming zero context tk until needed. This filesystem-based md is what enables progressive disclosure. Claude can navigate and selectively load exactly what each task requires.
M|Runt|tx|For complete details on the tc architecture, see [How Skills work](/en/doc/ag-and-tools/ag-skills/overview#how-skills-work) in the Skills overview.
M|MCP |tx|If your Skill uses MCP (md Context Protocol) tools, always use fully qualified tool names to avoid "tool not found" er.
M|MCP |**Fo|`ServerName:tool_name`
M|MCP |**Ex|
M|MCP |tx|```markdown  theme={null}
M|MCP |Use |bigquery_schema tool to retrieve table schemas.
M|MCP |Use |create_issue tool to cr issues.
M|MCP |tx|```
M|MCP |Wher|
M|MCP |it|`BigQuery` and `GitHub` are MCP server names
M|MCP |it|`bigquery_schema` and `create_issue` are the tool names within those servers
M|MCP |tx|w/o the server prefix, Claude may fail to locate the tool, esp when multiple MCP servers are available.
M|Avoi|Don'|
M|Avoi|tx|````markdown  theme={null}
M|Avoi|**Ba|Assumes installation**:
M|Avoi|tx|"Use the pdf library to process the file."
M|Avoi|**Go|Explicit abt dependencies**:
M|Avoi|"Ins|`pip install pypdf`
M|Avoi|Then|
M|Avoi|tx|```python
M|Avoi|tx|from pypdf import PdfReader
M|Avoi|tx|reader = PdfReader("file.pdf")
M|Avoi|tx|```"
M|Avoi|tx|````
M|YAML|tx|The SKILL.md frontmatter requires `name` (64 characters max) and `description` (1024 characters max) fields. See the [Skills overview](/en/doc/ag-and-tools/ag-skills/overview#skill-structure) for complete structure details.
M|Toke|tx|Keep SKILL.md body under 500 lines for optimal perf. If your cn exceeds this, split it into separate files using the progressive disclosure patterns described earlier. For architectural details, see the [Skills overview](/en/doc/ag-and-tools/ag-skills/overview#how-skills-work).
M|Chec|Befo|
M|Core|it|[ ] Description is specific and includes key terms
M|Core|it|[ ] Description includes both what the Skill does and when to use it
M|Core|it|[ ] SKILL.md body is under 500 lines
M|Core|it|[ ] Additional details are in separate files (if needed)
M|Core|it|[ ] No time-sensitive information (or in "old patterns" section)
M|Core|it|[ ] Consistent terminology throughout
M|Core|it|[ ] Examples are concrete, not abstract
M|Core|it|[ ] File references are one level deep
M|Core|it|[ ] Progressive disclosure used appropriately
M|Core|it|[ ] Workflows have clear steps
M|Code|it|[ ] Scripts solve problems rather than punt to Claude
M|Code|it|[ ] er handling is explicit and helpful
M|Code|it|[ ] No "voodoo constants" (all values justified)
M|Code|it|[ ] Required packages listed in instructions and verified as available
M|Code|it|[ ] Scripts have clear doc
M|Code|it|[ ] No Windows-style paths (all forward slashes)
M|Code|it|[ ] Validation/verification steps for ct operations
M|Code|it|[ ] Feedback loops included for qual-ct tasks
M|Test|it|[ ] At least three evaluations created
M|Test|it|[ ] Tested w/ Haiku, Sonnet, and Opus
M|Test|it|[ ] Tested w/ real usage scenarios
M|Test|it|[ ] Team feedback incorporated (if applicable)
